**Keonne Rodriguez**

| Occupation | [Software developer](/Software_developer) |
| :--------- | :--------------------------------------- |
| Known for  | Co-founder of [Samourai Wallet](/Samourai_Wallet) |
| Criminal penalty | Five years in prison, three years probation, $250,000 fine, forfeiture of assets (combined with Hill) |
| Website    | freesamourai.com                         |

Keonne Rodriguez is an American [software developer](/Software_development) renowned for his role as the co-founder of [Samourai Wallet](/Samourai_Wallet), a specialized [Bitcoin](/Bitcoin) wallet application. This particular software was meticulously engineered with the primary objective of significantly enhancing transaction privacy for individuals utilizing the Bitcoin network. In a development that garnered considerable attention and controversy in 2024, Rodriguez, alongside his fellow co-founder William Lonergan Hill, faced arrest. Subsequently, both individuals entered guilty pleas to charges stemming from their alleged operation of an unlicensed [money-transmitting business](/Money_transmitter), an accusation predicated on their creation and distribution of the very [software](/Software) that powered the Samourai Wallet application. This prosecution, rather predictably, ignited a firestorm of criticism from a diverse coalition of [privacy advocates](/Privacy) and [civil liberties](/Civil_liberties) organizations. These groups vehemently argued that the legal actions against Rodriguez and Hill represented a profound threat to the fundamental tenets of financial privacy, posed a chilling effect on the vital landscape of [open source development](/Open_source), and directly challenged the established principle of [code as speech](/Code_as_speech). It seems that merely writing and distributing code, even for privacy-enhancing tools, can now land one in the crosshairs of the state, a development many find less than ideal for technological progress or individual liberty.

In a curious turn of events that unfolded in December 2025, then-[President Trump](/Donald_Trump) publicly indicated that he would "look at" Rodriguez's case, suggesting the potential for a presidential pardon. One might wonder if such political gestures are born of genuine concern or merely opportunistic timing, but the prospect of intervention certainly adds another layer to this already complex narrative.

### Background

The genesis of Samourai Wallet traces back to 2015, when Keonne Rodriguez, alongside William Lonergan Hill, embarked on the venture of co-founding the platform. Their vision was to create a non-custodial wallet, meaning users retained full control over their private keys and, by extension, their funds—a critical distinction for those wary of centralized control. The paramount feature of Samourai Wallet was its capability to significantly improve privacy for on-chain Bitcoin transactions. This was achieved through the integration of sophisticated features, most notably "Whirlpool," a highly effective [coin-mixing](/Cryptocurrency_tumbler) service.

Whirlpool functions by taking individual bitcoin transactions and combining them with numerous other transactions from different users in a complex, multi-party exchange. This process effectively obfuscates the origins and destinations of specific coins, making it exceedingly difficult for external observers to trace the flow of funds through blockchain analysis. Rodriguez himself offered a particularly apt and rather elegant analogy to elucidate the service's mechanics. He stated, "I think the best analogy for it is like smelting gold. You take your bitcoin, you add it into [the coinjoin protocol] Whirlpool, and Whirlpool smelts it into new pieces that are not associated to the original piece." This description succinctly captures the transformative nature of the mixing process, where distinct transactional histories are deliberately broken and reformed, much like raw gold is melted down and recast into new, indistinguishable forms. The intention was clear: to provide users with a robust tool to reclaim and maintain their financial anonymity in a world increasingly moving towards pervasive digital surveillance.

### Legal Issues

The legal saga surrounding Keonne Rodriguez and Samourai Wallet commenced decisively on April 24, 2024, when the [U.S. Department of Justice](/United_States_Department_of_Justice) publicly announced the arrests of Rodriguez and Hill. Prosecutors from the [Southern District of New York](/Southern_District_of_New_York) brought forth serious allegations, contending that the mere creation and subsequent distribution of the Samourai Wallet [source code](/Source_code) amounted to the operation of an unlicensed money-transmitting business. Furthermore, they were charged with conspiracy to commit [money laundering](/Money_laundering).

The core of the prosecution's argument hinged on the assertion that by enabling users to obscure the transactional history of an estimated $2 billion in bitcoin, Rodriguez and Hill were, in effect, facilitating criminal activity. The Department of Justice (DOJ) specifically claimed that a staggering $100 million of illicit funds had been successfully laundered through the Samourai Wallet service. This accusation reframed the developers' privacy-enhancing software as a tool primarily for illicit financial flows, disregarding its legitimate use by individuals seeking to protect their financial privacy.

In a pivotal development in July 2025, both Rodriguez and Hill ultimately entered guilty pleas to the charges leveled against them. This plea agreement set the stage for Rodriguez's sentencing, which was initially scheduled for November 2025. On November 6, 2025, the court delivered its verdict: Keonne Rodriguez was sentenced to five years in prison, to be followed by a three-year period of probation upon his release. In addition to the custodial sentence, he was ordered to pay a substantial fine of $250,000. Further financial penalties included a joint agreement between Rodriguez and Hill to forfeit assets totaling just under $238 million combined. The sheer scale of these penalties underscored the severity with which the U.S. authorities viewed their activities, sending a clear, if controversial, message to the broader cryptocurrency and [open source development](/Open_source) communities.

### Reactions to Prosecution

The federal prosecution of Keonne Rodriguez has been met with widespread condemnation from a diverse array of organizations and individuals, particularly within the spheres of privacy and civil liberties. [Privacy advocates](/Privacy) have vociferously denounced the legal action, asserting that Samourai Wallet served a critical function in safeguarding its users' financial privacy—a right that many consider to be a [fundamental human right](/Human_rights). Critics of the prosecution argue, with considerable merit, that robust financial privacy is not merely a preference but an essential bulwark against unchecked [state surveillance](/Mass_surveillance) and potential [control](/Authoritarianism) over an individual's financial transactions and, by extension, other personal activities. The ability to transact without constant governmental oversight is seen as a cornerstone of personal autonomy in the digital age.

Furthermore, a significant contingent of Rodriguez's supporters has invoked the "[code as speech](/Code_as_speech)" doctrine, a legal principle famously established by the landmark case of [Bernstein v. United States](/Bernstein_v._United_States). This doctrine posits that computer code, like written or spoken language, is a form of protected speech under the First Amendment. Proponents of this view emphasize that Rodriguez's actions were limited to the creation and distribution of computer code—a technical expression, not the direct facilitation of illicit financial operations. To prosecute him for the potential misuse of his software, they argue, is akin to prosecuting a pen manufacturer for the crimes committed by someone who uses a pen to forge documents.

The implications of this prosecution have not gone unnoticed. [The Cato Institute](/Cato_Institute), a prominent libertarian think tank, articulated concerns that this case could engender a profound "chilling effect" across various communities. This chilling effect, they warned, could stifle innovation and advocacy among "cryptocurrency defenders, [human rights activists](/Human_rights_defender), privacy defenders, and software developers." Empirical evidence for this concern quickly emerged: Wasabi Wallet, another privacy-focused cryptocurrency mixing service, promptly moved to block users residing in the United States, while Phoenix Wallet was notably removed from American app stores, both actions directly attributable to the perceived regulatory and legal risks exemplified by the Samourai case.

Adding another layer of critique, other supporters of Rodriguez have drawn stark comparisons to the [2024 TD bank money laundering scandal](/TD_Bank_(United_States)). In that case, the [Justice Department](/United_States_Department_of_Justice) levied the largest penalty ever under the [Bank Secrecy Act](/Bank_Secrecy_Act) after discovering that bank employees had accepted bribes to actively facilitate money laundering. Despite the egregious nature of the bank's institutional failures and employee misconduct, the resolution primarily involved substantial financial penalties for the corporation, with a notable absence of jail sentences for the individuals directly involved. This contrast highlights what many perceive as a significant disparity in how the justice system treats large financial institutions versus independent software developers, especially when the latter are creating tools that challenge existing financial surveillance paradigms. Bitcoin users, who often value the decentralized and private nature of the cryptocurrency, have also voiced strong criticism of Rodriguez's prosecution, as many utilized Samourai Wallet precisely to [improve privacy](/Privacy-enhancing_technologies) in their own legitimate transactions.

In a testament to the resilient and decentralized nature of the [open-source](/Open_source) community, following the effective shutdown of Samourai Wallet, a collective of developers took the initiative in September 2024 to create the Ashigaru wallet. This new project is an [open-source](/Open_source) wallet built directly upon the foundational code of Samourai, ensuring that the principles of privacy and user control continue to be upheld and developed.

The political dimension of Rodriguez’s case was further complicated in December 2025, when then-President Donald Trump once again indicated his intention to examine the case and potentially issue a pardon for Rodriguez. This move, perhaps a nod to a segment of his political base that champions individual liberty and skepticism of government overreach, injected a layer of executive uncertainty into an already finalized legal outcome.

Rodriguez himself has not remained silent, commenting extensively on his case and its broader implications for the cryptocurrency ecosystem. He issued a stark warning, stating that "more builders in the space should be looking at what the government has done here, and really shoring up their defenses." He expressed a firm belief that other Bitcoin developers would inevitably be targeted next. Furthermore, he articulated a grim forecast, suggesting that if the Samourai wallet decision is taken to its "logical conclusion," [Bitcoin miners](/Bitcoin_miners) could subsequently become the next targets of [money transmission](/Money_transmitter) enforcement, effectively criminalizing core infrastructure components of the Bitcoin network itself. Such a scenario, if it were to unfold, would represent a significant escalation in the regulatory and legal battles over digital assets and privacy-enhancing technologies.

